And seeing that Prusias' persona] resources did not give him great strength, he won him the friendship of the other kings of that region and allied him with warlike nations. Prusias had quarrelled with Eumenes, king of Pergamum,2 a strong friend of the Romans, and they were fighting with each other by land and sea. But Eumenes was everywhere the stronger because of his alliance with the Romans, and for that reason Hannibal was the more eager for his over- throw, thinking that if he got rid of him, all his diffi- culties would be ended.

To cause his death, he formed the following plan. Within a few days they were intending to fight a decisive naval battle. He gave orders to collect the greatest possible number of venomous snakes and put them alive in earthenware jars.
